WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:14.240
All right, thank you guys for coming to this session and I'm so glad that Javier was the

00:00:14.240 --> 00:00:17.559
one that ran into AV issues and not me.

00:00:17.559 --> 00:00:24.639
So one of the things I learned from giving talks is that there's a very strong positive

00:00:24.639 --> 00:00:29.980
correlation between the number of memes and pictures you put in your slides and how happy

00:00:29.980 --> 00:00:35.459
the audience is, you know, from the session reviews I've been seeing.

00:00:35.459 --> 00:00:39.619
So I'm going to just put a bunch of pictures on here, I won't do too much talking, but

00:00:39.619 --> 00:00:45.660
at the end I'm going to do some demos because you do need some content in a tech talk.

00:00:45.660 --> 00:00:53.820
So we're going to be talking about mlflow and it's an open source platform for managing

00:00:53.820 --> 00:00:58.919
the machine learning lifecycle, whatever that means, we're going to find out in a little

00:00:58.919 --> 00:01:06.760
bit and it's a community driven project mostly led by the folks at Databricks with RStudio

00:01:06.760 --> 00:01:10.260
providing the R interface.

00:01:10.260 --> 00:01:17.400
So let's talk a little bit about the motivation for a project like this.

00:01:17.400 --> 00:01:23.940
One of the things that data scientists have trouble with sometimes is that you don't remember

00:01:23.940 --> 00:01:26.699
every model that you tried.

00:01:26.900 --> 00:01:31.779
So let's say you're building a neural net, you've got a few layers and maybe a residual

00:01:31.779 --> 00:01:37.699
connection here and there, and you stumble across some hyperparameters that seem promising,

00:01:37.699 --> 00:01:44.300
so you sort of go into that direction and tweak some numbers, and then, you know, maybe

00:01:44.300 --> 00:01:50.139
like an hour later you realize that, you know, the performance isn't great, so you want to

00:01:50.139 --> 00:01:56.099
sort of roll back to the previous version, but then you were so excited about your results

00:01:56.099 --> 00:02:00.900
you didn't bother, you know, pushing any of your, committing any of your code, so you

00:02:00.900 --> 00:02:03.699
don't remember what hyperparameters you used.

00:02:03.699 --> 00:02:13.179
So, you know, chuckle, please chuckle.

00:02:13.179 --> 00:02:18.539
So we're going to talk about how mlflow might, you know, help with that situation by logging

00:02:18.539 --> 00:02:22.419
your metrics and your hyperparameters.

00:02:22.419 --> 00:02:30.020
And another thing that sometimes people have issue with is replicating your results, and

00:02:30.020 --> 00:02:36.660
you might want to reproduce your teammates' numbers or you might just want to reproduce

00:02:36.660 --> 00:02:43.059
your own numbers from yesterday or last week or last quarter, and sometimes, you know,

00:02:43.059 --> 00:02:49.020
the code will run and then you'll get some maybe different results, maybe due to some,

00:02:49.020 --> 00:02:53.500
you know, random initialization of ways or whatnot, but sometimes it just doesn't work,

00:02:53.500 --> 00:03:02.179
you know, missing libraries, mismatched architectures, and not every data science project ends with

00:03:02.179 --> 00:03:06.699
a PowerPoint deck and a steering committee meeting.

00:03:06.699 --> 00:03:13.539
Sometimes you actually have to take the models to production, and, you know, it's hard to

00:03:13.539 --> 00:03:21.220
find common ground, depending on where you are, between the folks who prototype the models

00:03:21.220 --> 00:03:27.139
and the folks who actually need to take the models to production, and this is exacerbated

00:03:27.139 --> 00:03:32.179
by the fact that there are just so many different machine learning libraries out there, and

00:03:32.179 --> 00:03:35.860
there are also different deployment targets, right?

00:03:35.860 --> 00:03:40.979
So there are different libraries you can use to train the models, and then there are different

00:03:40.979 --> 00:03:43.699
ways to sort of deploy these models.

00:03:43.699 --> 00:03:54.059
So if you got, you know, the number of ways you can sort of combine the prototyping and

00:03:54.059 --> 00:03:57.899
the deployment just expands exponentially.

00:03:57.899 --> 00:04:07.100
So if you are at some specific companies, mostly out there in Silicon Valley, you might

00:04:07.100 --> 00:04:12.619
say, oh, you know, we got this all solved, but then what about everyone else?

00:04:12.619 --> 00:04:13.740
What do you do?

00:04:13.740 --> 00:04:18.579
So you'll go online, you'll do some Google searches, you'll be like, oh, what's everyone

00:04:18.579 --> 00:04:19.579
else doing?

00:04:19.579 --> 00:04:25.140
And then you'll find that, especially for model deployment, there are just so many different

00:04:25.140 --> 00:04:29.779
things out there, and it's kind of tough.

00:04:29.779 --> 00:04:35.660
So over the past couple years, there's been a lot of efforts in the machine learning community

00:04:36.299 --> 00:04:43.779
and also within the art community to try to solve these problems, or at least attempt

00:04:43.779 --> 00:04:45.619
to solve these problems.

00:04:45.619 --> 00:04:51.019
And I personally think that we won't ever come up with one framework that's just going

00:04:51.019 --> 00:04:59.940
to work for everyone, but I think we can try to segment the problems such that you can

00:04:59.940 --> 00:05:08.179
have a set of standard practices that sort of will apply to most people.

00:05:08.179 --> 00:05:15.660
So back to the topic, MLflow, it's got three different components.

00:05:15.660 --> 00:05:21.059
It's got tracking, which is going to help you keep track of your hyperparameters, some

00:05:21.059 --> 00:05:24.220
nodes and some metrics from your experiments.

00:05:24.220 --> 00:05:29.859
The project component bundles your project environment so others can reproduce your results.

00:05:29.859 --> 00:05:38.100
And the model component allows you to serialize and package your model so you can deploy them.

00:05:38.100 --> 00:05:42.380
So of course, you know, this doesn't make any sense, so we're going to do some demos

00:05:42.380 --> 00:05:47.820
to show what this thing actually looks like.

00:05:47.820 --> 00:05:53.420
And if I can figure out how I'm going to get there.

00:05:53.420 --> 00:05:54.420
All right.

00:05:54.420 --> 00:05:55.420
Here we go.

00:05:55.420 --> 00:05:56.420
Okay.

00:05:56.420 --> 00:05:58.420
So let's try to do this.

00:05:58.420 --> 00:06:04.619
So back row, can you give me a thumbs up if you can see or not?

00:06:04.619 --> 00:06:05.619
Okay.

00:06:05.619 --> 00:06:07.140
I think we're good.

00:06:07.140 --> 00:06:10.700
So we can load a library.

00:06:10.700 --> 00:06:14.380
By the way, this is on CRAN, so you can just install it off of CRAN.

00:06:14.380 --> 00:06:20.140
And I'm just going to do something really, really general right now.

00:06:20.140 --> 00:06:25.660
So we can say MLflow log param, and then let's say we want to log the food param, and then

00:06:25.660 --> 00:06:29.100
the value happens to be 42.

00:06:29.100 --> 00:06:37.420
So what is this doing in that background is it's basically launching a server and starting

00:06:37.420 --> 00:06:44.239
an experiment and actually logging, you know, this parameter.

00:06:44.239 --> 00:06:45.239
So we can come in here.

00:06:45.239 --> 00:06:47.380
Actually, let me take a step back.

00:06:47.380 --> 00:06:53.040
So this is like the default view of the MLflow interface.

00:06:53.040 --> 00:06:59.640
So we can go into our experiment run here, and then we see that our parameter field has

00:06:59.640 --> 00:07:01.160
been logged.

00:07:01.160 --> 00:07:11.720
So the cool thing is that this is not only for machine learning.

00:07:11.720 --> 00:07:20.260
If you have other experiments that you want to keep track of, you can also use this mechanism.

00:07:20.260 --> 00:07:24.459
So let's say now we want to log a metric.

00:07:24.459 --> 00:07:26.140
We come back here.

00:07:26.140 --> 00:07:31.339
We see that we have that metric that's been recorded.

00:07:31.339 --> 00:07:32.980
And there are other things you can do.

00:07:32.980 --> 00:07:34.579
There's tags.

00:07:34.579 --> 00:07:38.459
There are notes.

00:07:38.459 --> 00:07:43.540
You can write whatever you want.

00:07:43.540 --> 00:07:47.579
So that's sort of the tracking functionality.

00:07:47.579 --> 00:07:51.660
And we can now go to model.

00:07:51.660 --> 00:08:01.260
So Javier wrote a little XGBoost model to try to classify Iris, and then what we have

00:08:01.260 --> 00:08:11.959
here is a model to try to solve that same problem just using Keras and TensorFlow.

00:08:11.959 --> 00:08:14.459
So I'm going to run this real quick.

00:08:14.459 --> 00:08:23.380
So let's go through the code, standardizing values, normalizing values, and then here

00:08:23.380 --> 00:08:31.059
we can oh, actually, one thing I forgot to mention.

00:08:31.059 --> 00:08:37.700
When we log this parameter right here, we started an experiment run, and then after

00:08:37.700 --> 00:08:46.020
you're done with your experiment run, you need to end the run, and then once we do that,

00:08:46.020 --> 00:08:52.299
you can see that there's also a duration associated with your experiment run.

00:08:52.299 --> 00:08:59.659
So that might be helpful when you're trying to compare different ways to train the models.

00:08:59.659 --> 00:09:04.859
You might spend 10 hours to just get a little bit of accuracy, and that's not worth it.

00:09:05.539 --> 00:09:18.140
We can also use this context manager with the width function, and we can train this

00:09:18.140 --> 00:09:23.219
very simple neural net for a few epochs and see what happens.

00:09:23.219 --> 00:09:30.140
So you can see real time that the loss is going down, yeah, and the accuracy is going

00:09:30.140 --> 00:09:33.380
up, so we're doing great.

00:09:33.380 --> 00:09:43.340
And then we can go back to our UI, and we see that we have our neural net training run

00:09:43.340 --> 00:09:52.739
that has also been logged, and because we added a callback in the Keras model fit call,

00:09:52.739 --> 00:10:01.419
we can see that MLflow has also logged the accuracy for each epoch.

00:10:01.419 --> 00:10:11.340
So one other thing we did was we saved the model as an artifact.

00:10:11.340 --> 00:10:18.299
So you can basically save anything you want and associate it with an experiment.

00:10:18.299 --> 00:10:29.020
So what we can do right now is we can attempt to serve this model locally just using a web

00:10:29.020 --> 00:10:38.940
server, so using this function MLflow rfunc serve, and our model directory is the Keras

00:10:38.940 --> 00:10:50.140
model because that's where we logged it, and then we can provide the run identifier.

00:10:50.140 --> 00:10:56.140
So we'll do that, and then we got a model that's being served right now.

00:10:56.299 --> 00:11:00.539
It's port 8090, and then I got this prepared.

00:11:00.539 --> 00:11:09.299
So we can basically post a bunch of predictor data to this predict endpoint, and then see

00:11:09.299 --> 00:11:12.460
if we get some results back.

00:11:12.460 --> 00:11:17.340
So these are like the probabilities of each class.

00:11:17.340 --> 00:11:18.500
Okay.

