We can show a couple more things.

00:11:25.500 --> 00:11:31.099
You can also run projects from GitHub.

00:11:31.099 --> 00:11:40.780
So let's just do this real quick, and I can show what's going on there.

00:11:40.780 --> 00:11:47.380
So basically what this is doing is it's pulling code from GitHub and it's spinning up many

00:11:47.380 --> 00:11:54.539
environments to execute this code, and then it's going to log the results to a training

00:11:54.539 --> 00:12:09.219
run, and if we actually go to this URL and our entry point was this trend.r file, we

00:12:09.219 --> 00:12:19.099
see that we're using a random forest classifier now using Spark to try to classify the flowers.

00:12:19.099 --> 00:12:21.400
So we see that the run has succeeded.

00:12:21.400 --> 00:12:34.580
So we can go back to the available flow interface, and we see that here we have the parameters

00:12:34.580 --> 00:12:42.460
that were passed to the project run and then also some metrics associated with it, and

00:12:42.460 --> 00:12:51.539
the cool thing about this is that it records the exact commits on which this code was pulled

00:12:51.539 --> 00:12:58.419
from, so you can actually, you know, click on this to navigate a repository at that specific

00:12:58.419 --> 00:13:02.140
point in time.

00:13:02.140 --> 00:13:08.619
So I think that's all I have to show you guys, so, you know, definitely think about what

00:13:08.619 --> 00:13:15.960
sort of applications you can apply this to in your own endeavors.

00:13:15.960 --> 00:13:18.500
So I think do we have time for questions?

00:13:19.500 --> 00:13:24.099
Yep, we have some time for questions, if anybody has some.

00:13:32.099 --> 00:13:38.099
Kevin, one of the things I was wondering about, do you have to use the MLflow interface in

00:13:38.099 --> 00:13:43.580
order to retrieve the metrics which are recorded, or is it possible to export it to, you know,

00:13:43.580 --> 00:13:46.500
a flat file or some kind of log?

00:13:46.500 --> 00:13:56.539
Yeah, there's an API that you can use that's currently not exported yet in the R package,

00:13:56.539 --> 00:14:03.260
but there's a wrapper on the REST interface that you can use to potentially do that.

00:14:03.260 --> 00:14:07.419
So you don't have to use the interface if you don't want to, and then you can also build

00:14:07.419 --> 00:14:11.500
your own interface to suit your needs.

00:14:17.500 --> 00:14:22.500
